<h2 id="why-agencies-need-audit-partners">Why Agencies Need Audit Partners</h2>
<p>Digital agencies face a persistent tension between service quality and operational scalability. Website audits are essential to your client offering — they demonstrate expertise during the sales process, establish baselines for new engagements, and drive the strategic recommendations that justify retainer fees. But conducting thorough, professional-quality audits requires specialist skills and significant time investment that strain agency resources.</p>
<p>A single comprehensive website audit takes an experienced SEO analyst 15 to 25 hours to complete properly. For an agency managing twenty or more clients, that represents a full-time team member dedicated solely to auditing — not strategy, not implementation, not client management. Most agencies cannot justify that headcount, which leads to one of two compromises: audits that are rushed and superficial, or audits that are so time-consuming they become unprofitable.</p>
<p>The expertise gap compounds the capacity problem. A thorough audit requires deep knowledge of technical SEO, content strategy, backlink analysis, Core Web Vitals optimisation, and competitive intelligence. Few individual team members excel across all these areas. Hiring specialists for each discipline is prohibitively expensive for all but the largest agencies.</p>
<p>An audit partner solves both problems simultaneously. You get specialist-quality audits delivered at scale, without the overhead of building and maintaining an in-house audit team. Your analysts spend their time on strategy and implementation — the work that directly serves clients and drives retention — while the diagnostic heavy lifting is handled by dedicated experts.</p>
<p>The business case is straightforward. If your team spends 20 hours on an audit billed at £1,500, the effective hourly rate is £75. If you outsource the audit for £500 and bill the same £1,500, your margin increases by £1,000 while freeing 20 hours for billable client work. The partner model is not just operationally convenient — it is financially superior.</p>

<h2 id="white-label-audit-reports">White-Label Audit Reports</h2>
<p>White-label means the report carries your agency's branding with no mention of our involvement. Your clients see a professional document that reinforces your expertise and brand authority. As far as they know, the audit was conducted entirely by your team.</p>
<p>Every white-label report is delivered as a fully branded document featuring your agency logo, colour scheme, contact details, and brand voice. We format reports to match your existing deliverable templates where possible, ensuring consistency across your client communications. The report header, footer, cover page, and all attribution elements carry your identity exclusively.</p>
<p>The content of white-label reports matches the quality and depth of our direct-to-client audits. We do not produce a "lite" version for agencies. Your clients receive the same expert analysis, contextual interpretation, and actionable recommendations that we would deliver under our own brand. This quality standard protects your reputation and ensures the audit serves as a genuine value-add to your client relationships.</p>
<p>Reports are delivered in editable formats (Google Docs and PDF) so your team can review, annotate, and customise before presenting to clients. Some agencies pass through the report unchanged. Others add a cover letter, include additional context from their ongoing client relationship, or adjust recommendation priorities based on knowledge of the client's internal capabilities and budget. The editable format supports either approach.</p>
<p>Confidentiality is absolute. We do not contact your clients, reference the engagement publicly, or retain client data beyond the agreed retention period. Your client relationships are yours — we are infrastructure, not competition.</p>

<h2 id="wholesale-pricing">Wholesale Pricing</h2>
<p>Our agency pricing is structured to be profitable for you at any billing model — whether you mark up the audit cost, bundle it into retainer packages, or offer it as a value-add during the sales process.</p>
<p><strong>Standard wholesale pricing</strong> offers a significant discount from our direct-to-client rates. The exact discount depends on site complexity and volume commitment, but agencies typically pay 40-60% of the equivalent retail price. This margin creates room for healthy profitability at competitive client-facing prices.</p>
<p><strong>Site complexity tiers</strong> ensure you pay appropriately for each engagement. A 50-page brochure site requires less analysis time than a 5,000-page e-commerce platform. We define three tiers based on page count, technical complexity (JavaScript rendering, multilingual, multiple subdomains), and the number of competitors included in the benchmarking analysis. This tiered approach prevents you from overpaying for simple audits or underpaying for complex ones.</p>
<p><strong>Retainer pricing</strong> is available for agencies with predictable monthly audit volumes. A monthly commitment of four or more audits unlocks additional discounting and guaranteed turnaround times. Retainer arrangements also include a dedicated account manager who understands your agency's standards and client base, reducing the briefing overhead for each new audit.</p>
<p><strong>No minimum commitment</strong> is required to start. You can begin with a single audit to evaluate quality and fit before committing to volume. We are confident that the quality of the first report will demonstrate the value of an ongoing partnership, and we would rather earn your continued business through results than lock you into a contract prematurely.</p>
<p>All pricing is transparent and agreed upfront. There are no surprise charges for additional pages crawled, extra competitor analysis, or report revisions. The price quoted is the price you pay.</p>

<h2 id="how-it-works">How It Works</h2>
<p>The process is designed to be as lightweight as possible for your team. We handle the heavy lifting; you provide the brief and review the output.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1: Submit the brief.</strong> Share the client's website URL, target keywords or market, the specific concerns or goals driving the audit, and any branding assets for the white-label report. We provide a standardised briefing template that takes under ten minutes to complete. If you have existing data (Search Console access, analytics reports, previous audit findings), sharing it accelerates our analysis but is not required.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: We conduct the audit.</strong> Our team runs the full audit process: technical crawl, on-page analysis, content assessment, backlink review, competitive benchmarking, and Core Web Vitals evaluation. Throughout the process, we flag any unusual findings or questions to your team for clarification rather than making assumptions.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Quality review and branding.</strong> Every report goes through an internal quality review before branding. A senior analyst reviews the findings for accuracy, completeness, and prioritisation quality. Once approved, the report is formatted with your agency branding and delivered in your preferred format.</p>
<p><strong>Step 4: Delivery and support.</strong> You receive the completed report within the agreed turnaround time (typically five to seven business days for standard audits, three days for expedited requests). We include a brief analyst summary highlighting the most critical findings and recommended talking points for your client presentation. If your team has questions about any findings, we are available for a support call.</p>
<p><strong>Turnaround times</strong> are guaranteed. Standard delivery is five to seven business days from brief submission. Expedited delivery (three business days) is available for an additional fee. Emergency next-day turnaround is available on a case-by-case basis for urgent client needs.</p>

<h2 id="branding-and-customisation">Branding and Customisation</h2>
<p>Effective white-labelling goes beyond replacing a logo. The report should feel like a natural extension of your agency's existing deliverables, matching your communication style, design standards, and client relationship approach.</p>
<p><strong>Visual branding</strong> includes your logo on every page, your brand colours in headers, charts, and accent elements, your typography preferences where technically feasible, and your contact information in all relevant locations. We set up your brand template once and apply it to every subsequent report, ensuring consistency without repeated setup effort.</p>
<p><strong>Report structure</strong> can be customised to match your existing deliverable formats. If your clients expect a specific section order, a particular type of executive summary, or certain recurring elements (like a "what we did this month" section for retainer clients), we adapt our template to fit. Structural customisation is set up once during onboarding and applied to all future reports.</p>
<p><strong>Tone and language</strong> adjustments ensure the report reads as if your team wrote it. If your agency communicates in a casual, conversational tone, we match that. If your clients expect formal, corporate-style communication, we deliver accordingly. British or American English spelling conventions are applied based on your preference. We review samples of your existing deliverables during onboarding to calibrate our writing style.</p>
<p><strong>Custom sections</strong> can be added to the standard report template. Some agencies include a standing "next steps with us" section that transitions from audit findings to a service proposal. Others include a glossary of terms tailored to their typical client's technical sophistication. These custom sections are templated once and populated specifically for each report.</p>
<p><strong>Co-branding options</strong> are available if you prefer a "powered by" model rather than full white-label. Some agencies find that referencing an external audit specialist adds credibility rather than diminishing it. We support whatever positioning serves your client relationships best.</p>

<h2 id="volume-discounts">Volume Discounts</h2>
<p>Our pricing rewards consistency. The more audits you commission, the lower the per-audit cost, creating an incentive structure that benefits agencies as they scale their audit offering.</p>
<p><strong>Tier 1 (1-3 audits per month)</strong> receives standard wholesale pricing, which is already significantly discounted from retail rates. This tier suits agencies that use audits for new client onboarding or quarterly reviews and do not require a fixed monthly commitment.</p>
<p><strong>Tier 2 (4-9 audits per month)</strong> unlocks an additional 10-15% discount from standard wholesale pricing, plus guaranteed three-day turnaround on all standard audits. This tier includes a dedicated account manager who learns your agency's preferences and client patterns, reducing briefing time and improving report consistency.</p>
<p><strong>Tier 3 (10+ audits per month)</strong> provides maximum discounting with custom pricing negotiated based on your specific volume and mix of site complexities. This tier includes priority support, same-day turnaround availability, and quarterly business reviews where we analyse your audit portfolio for trends and opportunities to improve your client recommendations.</p>
<p><strong>Annual commitments</strong> offer additional savings over monthly arrangements. If you can commit to a minimum monthly volume for twelve months, we provide the next tier's pricing at your current volume. This means an agency committing to four audits per month for a year receives Tier 3-equivalent pricing from day one.</p>
<p>Volume discounts apply retroactively within each billing period. If you submit three audits in the first two weeks of a month and then a fourth, all four are billed at the Tier 2 rate. We calculate the best rate for you automatically rather than requiring you to predict your exact volume in advance.</p>
<p>All volume tiers include the same report quality and depth. We never reduce analysis quality to accommodate lower pricing — the discount reflects operational efficiencies from batch processing and the reduced client acquisition cost of ongoing partnerships, not reduced effort per audit.</p>

<h2 id="getting-started">Getting Started</h2>
<p>Starting an agency partnership is straightforward and carries no risk. We recommend a structured evaluation process that lets you assess quality and fit before committing to volume.</p>
<p><strong>Step 1: Initial consultation.</strong> Schedule a 30-minute call where we discuss your agency's audit needs, client profile, branding requirements, and expected volume. This call helps us tailor our onboarding to your specific situation and ensures we can deliver what you need before either side commits resources.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Trial audit.</strong> Commission a single audit at standard wholesale pricing. Choose a client site that represents your typical engagement — not the simplest or most complex case, but one that tests our ability to deliver relevant, actionable analysis for your client base. Review the report against your quality standards and gather feedback from the team members who would present it to clients.</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Onboarding.</strong> If the trial meets your standards, we complete the onboarding process: setting up your brand template, establishing communication protocols, agreeing on turnaround commitments, and configuring your preferred briefing and delivery workflows. Onboarding typically takes three to five business days.</p>
<p><strong>Step 4: Ongoing partnership.</strong> With onboarding complete, you can submit audit briefs on demand through our partner portal. Each audit follows the established workflow with minimal back-and-forth. Monthly invoicing with 30-day terms keeps your accounting simple.</p>
<p><strong>What we need from you to start:</strong> Your agency logo and brand guidelines (colours, fonts, tone), a sample of an existing deliverable for style matching, the URL and brief for your trial audit, and preferred contact details for your account team. That is everything required to produce your first white-label report.</p>
<p>Many of our agency partners started with a single trial audit and now commission ten or more per month. The partnership grows naturally as you see the quality, your team reclaims their time, and your clients receive better audit deliverables than you could produce in-house at the same cost. Use the form on this page to schedule your initial consultation and discuss how the partnership would work for your agency.</p>

